%#############################################################
\chapter{Population~\Pparen{}}
\label{chap:population}
%#############################################################

% ** \epigraph{The raging monster upon the land is population growth. 
% ** In its presence, sustainability is but a fragile theoretical concept.}{E.O. Wilson}
% \epigraph{The strongest witness is the vast population of the Earth to which we are 
% a burden and she scarcely can provide for our needs.}{Tertullian, (160-220AD)}
%%%% \epigraph{Human beings are a disease, a cancer of this planet.}{Agent Smith, The Matrix}
\epigraph{Literature is mostly about having sex and not much about having children. 
Life is the other way round.}{David Lodge\index{Lodge, David}}

Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} (repeated below for convenience) 
expresses human impact on the Earth as the product
of population~\Pparen{}, 
affluence~\Aparen{}, resource intensity of the economy~\Rparen{}, and
the impact of resources~\Xparen{}. 
Chapter~\ref{chap:planetary_boundaries} discussed how the Earth's ecosystems\index{ecosystem} 
provide for human needs and how human activities can degrade,
even catastrophically destroy, the ability of the Earth to support life. 

\begin{equation} 
  \iparx            \tag{\ref{eq:IPARX}}
\end{equation}

This chapter examines human population dynamics, that is, \mft{P} in the IPARX 
identity\index{IPARX identity}.
Section~\ref{sec:animal_pop} begins with a discussion of the impact~\Iparen{}
of human activities on animal populations.
The size of the impact is a direct result of the size of \mft{P}.
The recent, massive decline of many animal populations is concerning 
(in part) because it likely indicates a reduction in ecosystem services\index{ecosystem services}
brought about by human activities.

Section~\ref{sec:human_population} discusses human population.
Throughout history, the long-term trend has always been for the human population~\Pparen{} to grow,
which is (ultimately) unsustainable; 
see Section~\ref{sec:past_human_populations}.
Currently, population growth\index{population growth} has slowed (but not ceased).
Prospects for future human populations are discussed in Section~\ref{sec:population_modeling}
with an eye toward whether humanity will live sustainably in the future. 
The influence of economic output per person 
(\;\!\mft{A} in the IPARX equation)
on population growth\index{population growth} is discussed in Section~\ref{sec:dtt}.
Section~\ref{sec:pop_density} discusses the sustainability implications of population density. 

There are two schools of thought on population with relevance for economics and sustainability.
\textbf{Malthusians}\index{Malthusians}
think that population growth\index{population growth} will cause us to ``run out'' of 
scarce resources\index{resources, scarce}.
Techo-optimists\index{techo-optimists} think that more people will lead to 
better technology, more specialization of labor\index{labor!specialization}, and, ultimately, to a higher, not lower,
standard of living.
Interactions among 
population~\Pparen{}, 
affluence~\Aparen{}, and
resource~\Rparen{} scarcity
are discussed in Section~\ref{sec:malthus_ehrlich_simon}.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Animal populations}
\label{sec:animal_pop}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Currently, humans (36\%) and domestic livestock (60\%) constitute 96\% of the mass of
mammals on the planet \cite{BarOn2018}---only 4\% of the mass of mammals is 
wild animals such as whales\index{whale}, bison\index{bison}, deer\index{deer}, and bears\index{bear}. 
The number of wild vertebrates has declined by 68\% since 1970~\cite{WWFLPR2020}. 
Populations of insects are down about 80\% in the last 30 years~\cite{Hallmann2017}.
These statistics are alarming because they could indicate a drastic decline in the 
quality and/or quantity of ecosystem services\index{ecosystem services} available to animals 
(and potentially) humans.
One of the planetary boundaries\index{planetary boundaries} identified in Chapter~\ref{chap:planetary_boundaries} 
is an extinction rate of less than 0.001\% of species going extinct per year. 
Estimates vary, but all agree that the current extinction rate is more than ten 
times above this limit (0.01\% or greater).
It fact, the current crisis has been labeled a ``sixth mass extinction event.''
It is called the Holocene\index{Holocene} (or Anthropocene\index{Anthropocene})
extinction, because it began with 
megafauna extinctions thought to be the result of contact with early modern 
humans.
Thus, human-caused extinctions are not unique to the current century.
(Climate change\index{climate change} likely played a role in prehistoric mass extinctions, just as 
it does in the present crisis.)
% https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/apr/01/butterfly-numbers-fall-by-84-in-netherlands-over-130-years-study
% https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2018/10/30/18042150/wwf-living-planet-report-vertebrate-loss
% https://www.pnas.org/content/115/44/11262 -- it will take millions of years to recover the species we've already lost.

We should distinguish between the reason(s) and the mechanism(s) for 
the decline in animal populations. 
Population decline is an impact (\:\!\mft{I}) from the left-hand side of 
Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}. 
The reason(s) (that is, the ``why'') are given on the right-hand side of
Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}, namely the \mft{PARX} terms.
In contrast, the mechanisms (that is, the ``how'') behind the decline 
in animal populations are not provided by Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}.
Four important mechanisms are summarized below.
First, habitat destruction\index{habitat loss} plays an important role in the decline of animal populations. 
For example, in 1875 there was a swarm of Rocky Mountain locusts\index{Rocky Mountain locust} consisting of 
an estimated 12.5 trillion individuals, 
weighing 27.5 million tons, and covering an area larger
the state of California\index{California}. 
By 1902, the species was extinct, mainly because farming destroyed their 
breeding grounds. 
(Chapter~\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning} will discuss human alteration of the land.)
A second cause of animal population decline is overconsumption by humans.
Ocean fish stocks are a notable example, partly because of the role they play in human diets.
Other examples include
passenger pigeons\index{pigeons}, whales\index{whale}, 
bison\index{bison}, and megafauna such as the aurochs\index{auroch} and the giant ground sloth\index{sloth}.
A third cause of the decline in animal populations is human-induced climate change\index{climate change}.
For example, many Arctic species, such as polar bear\index{bear!polar} and walrus\index{walrus}, are struggling
to adapt to a warming planet.
Lastly, human contamination of the environment, either intentionally or unintentionally,
is a cause for the decline of many species.
For example, widespread use of insecticides\index{insecticide} in agriculture is thought to be a strong 
factor for the decline in many insect populations. 
Bees\index{bee} are a particularly alarming example of insecticide\index{insecticide}-driven species decline  
because of the valuable role bees\index{bee} play in pollinating human crops.


