%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Past human populations}
\label{sec:past_human_populations}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

There is an aphorism, 
``[i]t is difficult to make predictions, especially about the future.''
Indeed, predictions about future human populations vary considerably.
But it is also difficult to make predictions about the past.
Although scientists have estimated past population levels, reliable data are limited.
%\textit{Homo sapiens} probably emerged as a species 100,000 to 200,00 years ago.
In prehistoric times, the human population grew slowly.
By 9000~BC, there were 5--10~million human beings.
Around the year 1~AD, there were around 300~million people, 
representing an average growth rate of about 0.1\%/year.
By 1650~AD, the world population was around 500~million. 
Population growth\index{population growth} slowed because trade and urbanization\index{urbanization} spread infectious 
diseases that killed large numbers of people.
For instance, the Black Death\index{Black Death} killed 75--200~million people in the 1300s.
World population reached 1~billion (that is, 1000~million) around 1800~AD.
Population is affected by births and deaths.
Estimating the populations of antiquity is difficult because 
the birth and death rates are uncertain.
However, estimates of the total number of humans to have ever lived are 100--110~billion.
Thus, today's population of about 8~billion represents 8--9\% 
of all the people who have ever lived.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Population modeling}\index{population modeling}
\label{sec:population_modeling}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Whether the human population will continue to grow is a key 
sustainability question.
Human population in the future depends on only three factors:
current population (known more-or-less accurately), 
birth rate, and death rate.
If the number of births per year exceeds the number of deaths per year,
the population will grow.
If deaths exceed births, the population will fall.
Population is stable when births and deaths are equal.

A larger population has the capacity for more births and more deaths per year.
Thus, births and deaths per year depend on the size of the population.
The population growth rate\index{population growth rate}, in~\%/yr, on the other hand, expresses growth in a way that is
independent of population size.
If the population growth rate\index{population growth rate}
(in \%/year) is constant,
population grows exponentially\index{exponential growth}; see Section~\ref{sec:exp}.
Even if the population growth rate\index{population growth rate} changes slightly over time (as it has over the
last sixty years, dropping from about 2\%/year to about 1\%/year),
exponential growth\index{exponential growth} is a good
description of how population changes with time.

Figure~\ref{fig:UN_population_prospect} shows projections made by the United Nations\index{United Nations}
about the future human population. 
Because birth rate and death rate are influenced by many other factors---environmental, 
social, and economic---there exists a wide range of uncertainty in the population 
projections caused by uncertainty about future birth and death rates.
Indeed, Figure~\ref{fig:UN_population_prospect} contains both the possibility
that world population will peak around 2050 and the possibility
that population will keep rising to the end of the century.

