The UN\index{United Nations} projections shown in Figure~\ref{fig:UN_population_prospect} are not based on 
the World3\index{World3} model. 
Instead, the UN\index{United Nations}
used a Bayesian model\index{Bayesian model}
that accounts for correlations among the 
many variables assumed to affect birth and death rates.
The UN\index{United Nations} model also accounts for different levels of development in 
different segments of the Earth's human population.
Accounting for interactions among social, demographic, and economic
variables is expected to give more-realistic population projections.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Demographic transition theory}
\label{sec:dtt}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
%% https://pages.uwc.edu/keith.montgomery/Demotrans/demtran.htm -- on the Wayback Machine!

Thus far, we have used birth rate and death rate to mean number per year, and noted
that the rates depend on the size of the population.
To compare different populations (for instance, in time, or in different countries),
it is useful to have a way to express birth and death rates that are independent
of the total population.
The crude birth rate (CBR)\index{crude birth rate (CBR)} is the number of births per year per thousand people.
The crude death rate (CDR)\index{crude death rate (CDR)} is the number of deaths per year per thousand people.
``Crude'' indicates that the rates are uncorrected for
age (different generations could have different birth or death rates) or
sex (possible different number males and females in each age cohort).
The \textbf{replacement rate}\index{replacement rate} refers to the fact that, on average, each female needs to give
birth to 2.1 children over her lifetime to maintain a stable population,
to account for childhood mortality.

\textbf{Demographic transition theory}\index{demographic transition theory},
is based on an observed pattern of population change thought to be caused by
economic development.
Figure~\ref{fig:dtt} illustrates schematically the four stages of the transition.
In a developing society (low \mft{A}),
birth rates and death rates (per thousand per year) are high but nearly balanced,
resulting in low population growth\index{population growth}.
Later, the birth rate falls.
Thus, population is predicted to first grow rapidly and then stabilize.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Demographic transition theory\index{demographic transition theory}
gives us some hope for sustainability, namely, that
the total human population~\Pparen{} won't continue to grow exponentially\index{exponential growth}.
On the other hand, slowing of growth is predicated on increasing GDP per capita
(the \mft{A} term in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}).
\end{mcframe}


