The first stage of the demographic transition\index{demographic transition} is characterized by high birth and
death rates (Figure~\ref{fig:dtt_crude_rates}), with a consequently low rate of population growth\index{population growth rate}.
The first stage is typically resource constrained.
Until about 1800 AD the world was in Stage~1.
Economic development (increasing \mft{A}) initiates Stage~2 via public health measures,
improved sanitation, medical developments, and increasing agricultural productivity\index{productivity!agricultural}.
Stage~2 retains the high birth rate from Stage~1 but the death rate falls sharply
(particularly for childhood mortality).
The result is a rapid increase in population (Figure~\ref{fig:dtt_population}), 
with many young people; see Figure~\ref{fig:dtt_pop_pyramid}.
In Stage~3, changing economic conditions (such as increasing urbanization\index{urbanization}, a
transition away from an economy dependent on agriculture, and availability of
contraception) lead to a declining birth rate.
In Stage~3, the birth rate is still greater than the death rate, so the population
is still growing, but the falling birth rate means slower growth and an age structure
that begins to be more uniform.
In Stage~4, the birth rate and death rate equalize and the population stabilizes.

After the demographic transition\index{demographic transition},
the birth rate might rise again (causing further population growth\index{population growth})
or drop below the death rate, which leads to a decrease in total population.
Currently, most developed countries have a birth rate that is below the
replacement rate\index{replacement rate}, that is, a falling population (offset, in some cases,
by immigration\index{migration}).
As stated earlier, low birth rates are correlated to higher affluence~\Aparen{}.

As countries move through the demographic transition\index{demographic transition},
the age structure of the
population changes; see Figure~\ref{fig:dtt_pop_pyramid}.
A \textbf{population pyramid}\index{population pyramid}
shows the percentage of the population in each age cohort, of
each sex.
(Important note: a population pyramid\index{population pyramid} is always relative to the size of
the total population.)
The age structure of a population provides a lot of information about the population's
future and its economic outlook.
Stage~1 has many young people and few old people.
In Stage~2, more young people are being born and people are living longer.
Both of these groups are not of working age and tend to contribute little to GDP.
(In fact, they are dependents who consume rather than generate income\index{income}.)
Later, in Stage~3, as young people mature and join the labor market\index{labor market} and the
birth rate falls,
the fraction of the population that is working is much higher,
which generates a \textbf{demographic dividend}\index{demographic dividend}.
GDP per capita is higher because the fraction of the population that
is working is higher.
Finally, in Stage~4 the age distribution of the population stabilizes.
If birthrates continue to fall,
the population pyramid\index{population pyramid} becomes ``top heavy,'' and there is a higher proportion
of retirees to workers.
GDP per capita is lower than it would be with a different age structure.
(There can still be growth in GDP per capita, but growth faces a
demographic ``headwind.'')

The age structure of the population also shows \textbf{demographic momentum}\index{demographic momentum}.
It takes a lifetime to age a cohort out of the population pyramid\index{population pyramid}.
The next generation of parents have already been born.
The children of today will become the parents of tomorrow (that is, of the next generation).
A falling birth rate doesn't immediately lower the total population;
it takes time for the population to stabilize.
Conversely, a small cohort of parents, even if they have a high birth rate, cannot
increase total population size if the oldest generations are a large proportion
of the total population.
The overall death rate will still be greater than the overall birth rate because of
the sizes of the relevant age cohorts.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Distribution of population}
\label{sec:pop_density}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Where do people live?
Where should people live to be more sustainable?
\textbf{Population density}\index{population density}, the number of people per area, is a key
metric for sustainability.
For example, high population density\index{population density}, characteristic of urban areas, enables
cost-effective mass transit, which reduces carbon emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!transportation} from transportation.
Concentrating human population into a few high-density areas excludes most animal
species from those locations.
In theory, concentration in a few spots allows other areas to be ``spared,''
or dedicated for animal use.
In contrast, the ``sharing'' paradigm disperses human impact more broadly.
Chapter~\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning} discusses in more detail the
land-sharing versus land-sparing paradigm. 
There is a strong connection between population density\index{population density} and land use.
What density\index{population density} is ``best'' for sustainability depends on which factors
are being considered; there is no one ``right'' answer.

