Since the industrial revolution, humans are increasingly living in urban environments.
In 1973 there were only 3 cities (Mexico City\index{Mexico City}, Tokyo\index{Tokyo}, and
New York\index{New York} City) with populations
of more than 10~million people (called ``megacities'').
Since 2005--2006 more than half of the world's population live in urban areas, and
there are now 21 megacities.
The percentage of people living in urban areas is projected to grow to 68\% by 2050.
Urban living is correlated with wealth\index{wealth} and higher GDP.
High population density\index{population density} (number of people per area) means mass transit is practical
and, in fact, widely used.
Some thinkers have suggested that the densest urban environments are the most
ecological places to live~\cite{Owen:2004wt}.
However, urban areas are supported by vast networks, including transportation,
that supply resources, such as food.
Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} indicates that higher affluence~\Aparen{}, not location, is a
main source of ecological impact.
High population density\index{population density} can provide efficient transportation, 
minimize habitat destruction\index{habitat loss}, and allow economies of scale for dealing with waste\index{waste} materials.
Nevertheless, it is unwise to consider urban areas apart from the rural
areas that enable them to thrive.
True sustainability thinking must consider all of human society and its spatial distribution.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Malthus, Ehrlich, and Simon}\index{Malthus, Thomas}\index{Ehrlich, Paul}
\label{sec:malthus_ehrlich_simon}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Various writers, thinkers, and scholars throughout the world, from antiquity to
the present time, have predicted that population growth\index{population growth}
would cause resource scarcity.
Thomas Malthus\index{Malthus, Thomas} (1766--1834), wrote a book in 1798 suggesting that any increase in
affluence was only temporary.
He thought that any abundance of resources (such as food) would cause population
growth, which would immediately consume the abundance.
Increasing affluence, Malthus\index{Malthus, Thomas} thought, would lead to population growth\index{population growth}, which
would thereby decrease GDP per capita.
(In Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX},
affluence is measured by GDP per capita, \mft{A}\:\!)
Implicitly, Malthus\index{Malthus, Thomas} assumed that population would grow more rapidly than affluence.
The (hypothetical) inability to achieve long-term increases in affluence is
now called the \textbf{Malthusian trap}\index{Malthusian trap}.
Subsequent to Malthus'\index{Malthus, Thomas} work,
the Industrial Revolution occurred, and GDP per capita rose
in spite of, or alongside of, increasing population;
see Figures~\ref{fig:PopulationGraph} and~\ref{fig:AffluenceGraph-Nordhaus}.

Nevertheless, fears of Malthusian\index{Malthusian} catastrophe have not gone away.
Two influential modern neo-Malthusian\index{Malthusian} works are \emph{The Population Bomb} (1968),
by Paul Ehrlich\index{Ehrlich, Paul}, and \emph{Limits to Growth} (1972), commissioned by the Club of
Rome.\index{Club of Rome}
\emph{Limits to Growth} warned of ``a rather sudden and uncontrollable decline
in both population and industrial capacity'' due to exponential growth\index{exponential growth} in the
rate of use of nonrenewable resources.
Likewise, \emph{The Population Bomb} predicted that in ``the 1970s hundreds of
millions of people will starve to death.''
Neither prediction came to pass.
Nevertheless, both books have received multiple updates, repeating the same basic claims.

The opposite point of view has been called \textbf{techno-optimism}\index{techno-optimism}.
\textbf{Techno-optimists}\index{techno-optimists} hold that there are no limits to growth, because
(a)~matter and energy are abundant in the universe and
(b)~human ingenuity can invent technology 
to enable \textbf{substitution}\index{substitution} for all depleting
nonrenewable resources.
The economy is the mechanism by which techno-optimists\index{techno-optimists} expect human ingenuity
to overcome all resource scarcities.
The price of any scarce resource will rise, thereby incentivizing development and use of
alternative resources.
\emph{Limits to Growth} assumed pollution\index{pollution} would grow exponentially\index{exponential growth} but
pollution-control technology would not.
Techno-optimists\index{techno-optimists}, on the other had, claim that it is technologically possible to produce,
for example, abundant energy with little to no pollution\index{pollution}.
They point to the growth of wind and solar
electricity generation\index{electricity generation} technologies as examples.

Who is correct, the neo-Malthusians\index{Malthusians} or the techno-optimists\index{techno-optimists}?
Will population growth\index{population growth} lead to catastrophe or is growth a source of labor\index{labor} and
technology that will yield abundant resources\index{resources, abundant}?
In 1980, business professor Julian Simon\index{Simon, Julian}
challenged biologist Paul Ehrlich\index{Ehrlich, Paul} to a
\$10,000 wager.
Ehrlich\index{Ehrlich, Paul} was to select a suite of raw materials and a date more than a year away.
If inflation-adjusted prices of those raw materials increased
(indicating scarcity), Ehrlich\index{Ehrlich, Paul} would win.
Ehrlich\index{Ehrlich, Paul} chose
copper\index{copper (Cu)}, chromium\index{chromium (Cr)}, nickel\index{nickel (Ni)},
tin\index{tin (Sn)}, and tungsten\index{tungsten (W)} 
over the time period 1980 to 1990.
In the 1980s, world population increased from about 4.46~billion to around
5.33~billion.
Despite the largest single-decade population increase in history,
prices for all five materials decreased (indicating abundance), and
Simon\index{Simon, Julian} won the bet.
If you think the price decreases settled the argument, you lose, like Ehrlich\index{Ehrlich, Paul}.
Over the years, both sides have countered with a variety of ``what-if'' scenarios, and
scholars have examined other timespans and other raw materials.
One study concluded that Simon\index{Simon, Julian} would win about 54\% of the time
if war years were included and
about 70\% of the time if war years were excluded~\cite{Pooley:2020vx}.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Malthusians\index{Malthusians} think that population growth\index{population growth}
will lead to scarcity of finite resources.
Therefore, they expect prices of scarce resources\index{resources, scarce} to increase.
Techno-optimists\index{techno-optimists}, on the other hand, expect that human-created technology will
create new sources of resources.
Rather than scarcity causing prices to rise, resources should be abundant and
prices should fall with a growing population.
\end{mcframe}

The path of wisdom avoids false dichotomies.
Likely, there are true elements to both sides of this debate.
% Which components and which areas are correct and helpful for guiding future policy
% and which are not remains to be seen.
It is certainly true that a finite planet does not contain infinite resources.
Exponential economic growth\index{exponential growth}
can't continue forever with finite resources.
On the other hand, we've done pretty well so far and, by most measures, human
life is better now than it has ever been.
% Whether you believe that will continue and, if so, for how long seems to depend
% largely on what your viewpoint is.
Whether you believe that human life can, or will, continue to improve and, if so, for how long,
likely depends on your prior beliefs about human ingenuity,
the role of the economy, and
the substitutability\index{substitution} of critical resources.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Summary}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

This chapter illustrated some of the reasons why population~(\:\!\mft{P} in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX})
is a key consideration for sustainability.
The scale of human population determines the extent of our impact on the planet
through our economic activity.
Conversely, it is also our economic system that incentivizes
a reduction in population growth\index{population growth} (or seems to).
While human population has grown exponentially\index{exponential growth},
there are signs that trend is slowing
and may even reverse.
The next chapter will consider ways in which human affluence~\Aparen{} affects sustainability.


